    </td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td>
      <p><a href="images/crusader/crushtexch.jpg"><img SRC="images/crusader/small/crushtexch_small1.jpg" BORDER=0 ALT width="100" height="75" align="right"></a>The Crusader is the first powered armor designed for
    multi-environmental operation. With no retrofitting, modification, or extraneous
    preparation, the Crusader can operate in a land conflict, board ship, space, and stage a
    boarding assault in a zero atmoshere, zero gee environment. Three components allow the
    Crusader to perform in this fashion. First is the force sealed canopy which creates an
    airtight seal. Second are the jump jets in the shoulders and feet of the suit. A
    biofeedback system as well as a sophisticated AI allow for precise manuvers both in space
    and in land based combat. Third and perhaps most important is the heat exchanger on the
    rear of the suit. Seen here, the exchanger is often referred to as the 'bustle' due to
    it's location and resemblence to the ladies dress fasion of centuries ago. The heat
    exchanger allows the suit to shed excess temperature in deep space through the forced
    collection and dispersal of heat. The bustle is actually made up of thousands of thin
    fins, essentially producing a tremendous amount of surface area in a small space. All of
    this area allows the Crusader to radiate heat at a sustantial pace. It is easiest for the
    pilot to simply rotate the legs until the bustle is in darkness, shielded from the heat of
    a star, and let the fins directly radiate their heat into space. This manuver is best used
    while on deep space manuvers as the suits bodily configuration at this point isn't always
    conducive to assaults.</p>
